   "source": [
    "# Discussion Questions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8166c5f0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Describe your reaction to the match rate. What sources of data might be prone to privacy issues?"
The match rate shows that even when direct identifiers such as names are removed, it is still possible to re-identify individuals by linking anonymized data with another dataset. Using only age, gender, and the first three digits of a ZIP code was enough to uniquely match some records. This demonstrates that anonymized datasets can still pose privacy risks if they contain quasi-identifiers that can be cross-referenced with other available data.Many real-world data sources may be vulnerable to this type of privacy issue. For example, healthcare datasets, voter registration records, and social media profiles often contain demographic information such as age, location, and gender. When these datasets are combined with publicly available information, individuals may be re-identified even if their names were removed. This shows that simply removing names is not always enough to protect privacy.
   ]
